<subSubSection id="6DB40C7386F5C6EBDA34A1D2328C725A" pageId="14" pageNumber="99" type="notes">
<paragraph id="9DBC0B7DB382E58DC8C0BBC018D9BC1F" pageId="14" pageNumber="99">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0C116430D2A4AD4E304E024119D9E1DD" pageId="14" pageNumber="99">
The observed population of 
<taxonomicName id="406A26676F1FBA64F9420958C30EC5D0" genus="C." lsidName="C. waisaliensis" pageId="14" pageNumber="99" rank="species" species="waisaliensis">
<emphasis id="5CD73D306D270B33BB28F72793C05CED" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="99">C. waisaliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was comprised of ca. 20 individuals, many of which were reproductive. A single individual appeared to be of hybrid origin, with the putative parents being 
<taxonomicName id="008B0D9FB4F707C69893B03E666B62C8" genus="C." lsidName="C. waisaliensis" pageId="14" pageNumber="99" rank="species" species="waisaliensis">
<emphasis id="871E77C79810430801B59126E8B358A2" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="99">C. waisaliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="141950B8623065CACFCB6F97154020E4" genus="C." lsidName="C. cephalophora" pageId="14" pageNumber="99" rank="species" species="cephalophora">
<emphasis id="A834496F652E165E8686977E0B2D3FCE" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="99">C. cephalophora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on morphological characters intermediate between these two species.
</paragraph>
